It's an auditorium. It has a huge stage, and resembles the one that you saw in Mikhail's execution. Multiple rows of seats are laid out for a crowd to sit in, and it looks like it can easily hold a few hundred people. There are 2 huge double doors, one of which you just walked through, and they lead out to the seating area. To get on the stage, there's a small plight of steps that lead up. On the stage currently is a podium and behind that is Japan's flag. Looking out at the seats, they're all made of fine leather. It's quite comfortable to sit on. Hanging above are multiple lights, situated in a grid format. There are many of them. Of course, this is also a large room, so the ventilation system in here is a bit more grueling than most. There's a huge vent to the side, blowing in fresh air. On the stage, there isn't much. You can practically see the whole crowd from up here, but there's no point since... well, all the seats are empty. The more interesting things are featured backstage. There are multiple switches and levers back here. This isn't an ordinary stage. There's a switch for the curtains, and another activating the rotating section of the stage (see the musical 'Hamilton' for reference). There are steps up to higher sections of the stage for scenes like Romeo and Juliet's balcony scene. These elevated sections are also on wheels and can be pushed around, though without multiple people or considerable arm strength it can be hard. On top of that, a ladder backstage leads to the very top of the stage where you can move around spotlights and control lighting. The huge spotlights also have color controls. (edited)
